                <h2>Project 1: Multimodal Obstacle Essay</h2>
                <div class="project-content" style="max-width: 850px; margin: 0 auto;">
                    <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Introduction</h3>
                    <p>This section outlines one of my biggest struggles during the secondary school level; not making the school team for my first basketball tryouts. It was hard. Basketball was one of my passions and for that reason, I envisioned that I was ready. But the very unfortunate reality was that my name did not seem to be on the list. There was more to it than my name absent. I sorely lacked the necessary willpower, discipline, tenacity and approach to how I was going to accomplish my other life goals. This type of failing, I later turned around to say, was the greatest lesson of my life. It showed me how discipline brings order, how obstacles can be transformed into motivation, and how the greatest growth is the result of sustained, continuous effort.</p>

                    <p>The most important aspect of life is that it is more than basketball to me. There's got to be more to life than what most people see as the crucial point. The lesson illuminated my life and helped me survive the hardships that school, life in general, and the future job that I envisioned posed. If I had the chance, I would love to show you how this experience transformed my life. I would do this using the concepts of discipline, effort as the base to growth, and resilience.</p>

                    <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Discipline</h3>
                    <p>My love affair with basketball, which by the way, I would say would be the most important part of my existence, began in the gym. The feeling is almost ethereal, the imaginings, the feeling of pounding the court and 'owning' it, the feeling of making 'that' shot that 'must' be made, the feeling of being with the 'perfect' basketball team and 'becoming' part of that 'brotherhood' can be my 'home' … no, my 'sanctuary'." The open gym was a place to escape from the cruel and harsh realities of life. During this time the only signals your body gets is that of a basketball being thrown and it hitting the floor. Basketball was more than a sport to me, it was an escape, it was everything.</p>

                    <p>However, I learned from not making the team that passion alone would not suffice. I had to dedicate myself to a greater degree of discipline. I created a schedule: after school, practice followed the running, then the workouts to enhance the conditioning, and finally analyzing the techniques of the professionals. Every missed shot and every careless drill was not a failure anymore, but a score. It was a piece of evidence of what required attention. I learned how to embrace my errors and understand that they carry valuable lessons. I am still guided by that change today. If I ever encounter a tough topic and Iam in college, I do not view a poor score as an indicator that I am incapable. I view it as I would a missed jump shot – an opportunity to alter my approach and enhance my performance. Setting aside my structured study hours to analyze my performance in the game, I understand that as in basketball, I adjust my approach: I analyze my answers, identify all my mistakes, and discipline myself to reach my goals. It is discipline. It is a discipline that I have come to understand is a skill that is not only relevant to my performance on the court. It is a skill that has allowed me to to stay on course in my life.</p>

                    <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Effort Leads to Growth</h3>
                    <p>Delay of effort proved to be the most paying lesson of all, since the most enduring one has to with growth. I tried out again the next year, I did not all of a sudden become the best player on the court. I was fit, my dribbling was better, and my confidence went up. I was able to make the team.</p>
                    
                    <p>That moment was much more than basketball. It was the proof that effort over time alters the outcome. It showed me that ability that is natural can open the door, but effort is what takes you through it. The lesson continues to shape my day to day life. College is a different kind of stamina. The late hours of studying, trying to balance commitments, and not forgetting to meet the expectations is exhausting. It is important to remind myself that overnight results do not happen. Growth comes gradually, but it always comes when effort is consistent.</p>
                    
                    <p>Honestly, it's wild how this stuff creeps into every part of life—not just school. Figuring out where I wanna go with finance and econ, picking up weird new skills (YouTube tutorials at 2 a.m., anyone?), or just trying to be a little less of a mess every day—I keep coming back to this idea: keep grinding, and you'll see something shift. Doesn't always look flashy, progress can be super slow, but hey, been there before. It adds up.</p>

                    <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 15px;">Resilience</h3>
                    <p>Oh man, speaking of plot twists—my back decided to go rogue and sideline me from basketball, which basically felt like someone hit the eject button on my identity. The gym was my happy place, suddenly replaced by, well, me glaring at the ceiling, annoyed as hell. Took a while, but somewhere in that mess, I figured out the bigger lesson: you get knocked down, you figure out how to get up stronger. That's resilience, right? Even if it comes with a bunch of grumbling and dramatic sighs.</p>
                    
                    <p>Man, that whole experience yanked me right outta my comfort zone. Suddenly, I'm knee-deep in other hobbies—like cooking, which I never saw coming as a legit creative escape. Somehow, chopping veggies and messing around with random spices became my thing. Plus, there's something about dishing out a meal to friends that makes you feel like you've actually got your life together.</p>

                    <p>Don't even get me started on music. When I couldn't hit the basketball court, I used playlists like therapy. Some days, I'd throw on something loud just to drown everything out; other times, I'd fall into a rabbit hole of weird new genres. It's wild how much a song can change your mood, right?</p>

                    <p>So, now? Resilience is kinda my secret cheat code. College hits you with curveballs—tough classes, awkward roommate pairings, existential panic at 2am, you name it. Every time I start spiraling, I remember those days without basketball. That forced pause taught me my story doesn't just end with a setback. Nah, sometimes you just level up in a new area. I guess now I just trust that if things go sideways, I'll cook up something, or blast a song, and, somehow, I'll keep rolling. Alright, let's land this thing. Getting axed from the basketball team that first year? Oof. Straight-up gut punch. I was just sitting there, simmering in that awful soup of embarrassment and… what, rage? Yeah, a little bit of that too. Felt like the universe had a personal vendetta against me or something. Now that I think about it, though... kinda ended up shaping me, even if I wanted to set the gym on fire back then.</p>

                    <p>Sure, missing varsity stung (spoiler: I'm not in the NBA today), but I ended up learning way more than how to dribble. Like, how to haul myself off the floor—literally and metaphorically—when life throws a wrench in my plans. If you want structure, you basically gotta DIY it. And resilience? Not just some motivational poster mumbo-jumbo—it's actual armor for surviving public faceplants.</p>

                    <p>I still lug these lessons around. Final exams, awkward breakups, even when my phone dies during an Uber ride—same bag of tricks, just new headaches. Turns out, hurdles aren't concrete barricades. They're more like those impossible IKEA puzzles that make you want to scream, but hey, you figure it out eventually. I could've rage-quit, chucked my sneakers in the trash, said "I'm done." But nope. Stubbornness? Determination? Masochism? Call it what you want, but it's still kicking.</p>

                    <p>So, what's the takeaway? Flopping doesn't mean Game Over. It's just an aggressively uncomfortable nudge to step it up. And let's be real, I'm still RSVPing to that party—clumsy moves and all.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div id="project2" class="content-section">
