                <h2>Project 2: Rhetorical Analysis of Slenderman Documentary</h2>
                <div class="project-content">
                    <p style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 10px;"><strong>Analysis Focus:</strong> HBO's <em>Slenderman</em> (2016), directed by Irene Taylor Brodsky</p>
                    <p style="text-align: center; margin-bottom: 30px;"><strong>Segment Analyzed:</strong> 00:12:10 – 00:18:10</p>
                    
                    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; font-size: 1.05em; line-height: 1.8;">
                        <p>HBO's <em>Slenderman</em> (2016), directed by Irene Taylor Brodsky, dives straight into the shocking 2014 stabbing in Waukesha, Wisconsin. Two girls, both just twelve—Morgan Geyser and Anissa Weier—attacked their friend because they believed it would please Slenderman, a creepy internet legend that started online. The documentary doesn't try to sensationalize what happened. Instead, Brodsky and her team dig into why it happened. They argue that the early, unfiltered internet became a dangerous playground for kids like Morgan and Anissa, who were left to wander its strangest corners alone. This wasn't just about two bad apples, they say—it's a complicated tragedy, born out of digital myths, teenage vulnerability, and untreated mental illness. Instead of just focusing on the horror, the film asks people to understand how something like this can happen, and to take it as a serious warning. For this analysis, I'm looking at the section from 00:12:10 to 00:18:10, which covers the girls' first steps into the world of Slenderman. Through careful analysis of how the filmmakers use cinematography, mise-en-scène, composition, editing, and sound, I will demonstrate how they drive home their point and push for more digital awareness and parental involvement.</p>

                        <p><em>Slenderman</em> came out in 2016, close on the heels of the 2014 stabbing and right in the middle of the court cases. That timing matters. People were already worried about how the internet and social media were changing kids. Platforms like YouTube and Creepypasta were everywhere, but most parents didn't really get what went on there. The filmmakers don't hide their opinion: they believe the digital world played a huge part in this tragedy. They point to the internet's algorithms, its anonymity, and the way it blurs fantasy and reality—all of which, in their view, pulled Morgan and Anissa in. The section I'm focusing on really lays out how the "infection" started online and spread into the girls' minds. The film doesn't ask viewers to pass judgment. Instead, it turns us into witnesses, watching two kids get swept up in something bigger than themselves, making it clear this is a failure of the system and not just individual evil.</p>

                        <p>The way the camera works in this part of the film pulls you in close, creating a voyeuristic descent that makes you feel like you're right there with the girls. It's both intimate and uncomfortable. The shots are tight, with lots of extreme close-ups that linger on the pixelated, eerie images of Slenderman on their screens at 00:12:25. As depicted in the documentary around this timestamp, the parents and investigators describe the disturbing nature of what the girls were viewing online. You see Morgan's and Anissa's eyes at 00:13:15, wide and locked in, creating a sense of tunnel vision where the rest of the world just disappears. It's claustrophobic. You're not watching from a safe distance; you're right there, falling down the rabbit hole with them.</p>

                        <p>When the camera shows the screens, it's head-on, positioning viewers to see exactly what the girls see. But when it shows the girls themselves, the angle often looks down from above at 00:14:50, almost as if the technology is looming over them. The documentary's narration around this moment discusses how children interact with technology and social media, emphasizing the power imbalance between vulnerable young minds and addictive digital platforms. They look small, hunched, and fragile—kids overwhelmed by something much bigger than themselves. This cinematographic choice reinforces the filmmakers' central argument that these children were victims of forces beyond their control.</p>

                        <p>The camera movement further emphasizes this entrapment. As the lens drifts slowly over creepy fan art and scrolls down endless forum posts at 00:15:30, it mimics the way you'd read or browse online, drawing you deeper into the digital world. There's nothing smooth or polished here; sometimes the camera feels shaky, almost hesitant, echoing the anxious, secretive way the girls are exploring this world. This technique doesn't just show the audience what the girls saw—it makes us experience the disorienting, addictive nature of their online journey.</p>

                        <p>Beyond the camera work, the staging throughout this segment highlights how the ordinary and the disturbing mix together in ways that feel deeply unsettling. Almost everything happens in bedrooms—places that are supposed to be safe for kids. There are stuffed animals, bright blankets, and schoolbooks visible at 00:13:40, all the usual signs of childhood innocence. But then there's the laptop, throwing an icy glow across the room. The danger isn't outside; it's right there, sitting on the bed or desk, invading what should be their safest space. Parents in the documentary discuss discovering their daughters on their computers late at night (around 00:14:00), describing how they found the girls absorbed in Slenderman content during hours when they should have been sleeping. The internet isn't just influencing them from afar; it's moved in, transforming a sanctuary into a portal for psychological invasion.</p>

                        <p>The lighting throughout these scenes reinforces this transformation. Everything is dark, with sharp contrasts where the only real light comes from the computer screen, casting deep shadows everywhere else at 00:14:10. This turns a familiar bedroom into something creepy. Suddenly, any shadow could be hiding Slenderman. The blue glow flickers on the girls' faces, sometimes making them look innocent, sometimes making them look haunted. It's unsettling and drives home just how much their world has changed. You can observe how this lighting choice creates what film scholars call "psychological realism," where the visual environment reflects the characters' internal emotional state.</p>

                        <p>The way this film is put together makes it increasingly hard to tell where reality ends and the digital world begins. It's a compositional choice that proves central to the filmmakers' argument. There's a clear split in the color palette that reinforces this boundary blurring. The bedroom (the "real" world) glows with soft, gentle colors. Look at the screens, though, and you're hit with harsh blacks, blinding whites, and sickly greens. The documentary's narration around 00:15:00 explains how Creepypasta and internet horror content affects young people's perception of reality. The online images look rough and grainy on purpose, almost like "found footage." That style tricks your eyes and brain, making the myth feel more real than it should, demonstrating how easily the line between fiction and reality can dissolve for vulnerable minds.</p>

                        <p>Even more striking is how the filmmakers layer digital content directly over the real world rather than keeping it confined to screens. You'll see Anissa sitting on her bed at 00:16:20, but floating over her image are ghostly fragments of text from a Creepypasta story. These jagged, diagonal lines slice through the calm, horizontal lines of her bed and the solid vertical of her body. It's as if the internet is crashing into her life, breaking through her safe space in a visual representation of psychological intrusion. The girl remains the center, the "positive space," but digital words start filling in every gap around her. You can almost see fiction creeping into her mind and her world, making the abstract concept of "internet influence" tangible and visible.</p>

                        <p>The editing throughout this section isn't just flashy. It's deliberately designed to mess with your head, mimicking how someone falls into an online obsession. Right away, you get hit with a barrage of images at 00:12:10 through 00:13:00: a YouTube thumbnail, a warped shot of Slenderman, a scream from a viral video, someone's fan art. Experts interviewed in the documentary discuss algorithm-driven content and digital "rabbit holes" that pull users deeper into niche content with each click. It's quick and jarring, like the feeling of doomscrolling late at night, sucked into an endless feed. You barely have time to process anything before the next shock lands. The pace makes it feel like you can't escape, conjuring this anxious, claustrophobic dread that mirrors the girls' own spiraling obsession.</p>

                        <p>This editing strategy also relies heavily on contrast to create emotional impact. One minute, you're watching shaky, creepy black and white footage of Slenderman. The next, you see Morgan and Anissa in a sunlit home video, laughing and playing between 00:17:00 and 00:17:30. Parents describe their daughters before the obsession began (around 00:17:15), recalling how they were normal, happy girls who loved typical childhood activities. This whiplash is the emotional heart of the film. It throws the innocence of childhood right up against the darkness they stumble into. That contrast isn't just sad; it's devastating. You feel the tragedy deeply, and everything that comes later seems both unavoidable and heartbreaking. The juxtaposition forces viewers to confront how quickly and completely a child's world can be transformed.</p>

                        <p>Sound does tremendous heavy lifting throughout this section, building what might be called an architecture of fear that supports the visual elements. There's this low, steady synth hum underneath almost everything from 00:12:15 onward. It doesn't belong to the girls' world; it's there to haunt you, to make Slenderman feel close even when he's not visible on screen. Add in those faint, warped whispers at 00:15:45—they're barely there, but they're enough to make the hair on your arms stand up. The documentary depicts how the girls described sensing Slenderman's presence (around 00:16:00), with testimony revealing their growing belief that he was watching them and communicating through the internet. These sounds pile on the paranoia and unease, echoing what's going on in the girls' heads and creating an auditory representation of psychological disturbance.</p>

                        <p>The filmmakers also make strategic use of diegetic sound. Real-world noises like mouse clicks, keyboard taps, and the sounds from the videos the girls are watching all appear in the mix. But even these familiar sounds get twisted, echoing weirdly or distorted until you're not sure what's real anymore. The confusion in the sound design matches the confusion on screen, blurring the line between reality and fiction in yet another layer. And then, at the very end of the segment, everything just stops. Complete silence descends at 00:18:05. It's jarring, and it leaves you alone with your thoughts, making the moment land even harder and forcing viewers to sit with the weight of what they've just witnessed.</p>

                        <p>Through these carefully orchestrated film techniques, the filmmakers weave in three classic rhetorical appeals to build their persuasive case. First, the film hits you right in the gut through pathos. You see the clash—sweet childhood moments up against scary, disturbing images. Close-ups of scared faces and creepy sounds pull out more than just fear. You feel pity, dread, and a deep concern for these kids. Parents make emotional statements throughout the documentary (particularly around 00:17:20) about their daughters and express profound guilt about not recognizing the warning signs earlier. The emotional manipulation is deliberate and effective, ensuring that viewers don't simply judge the girls as monsters but instead empathize with them as victims.</p>

                        <p>However, the filmmakers don't just tug at your heart. They lay out a logical chain of causation that appeals to logos. You watch as exposure to gripping online content leads to obsession, which then warps reality in a clear progression. They use actual websites, forums, and the same kinds of videos the girls probably saw, grounding the story in the real world rather than abstract speculation. This logical framework suggests that given similar circumstances, other children could follow the same dangerous path, making the case that systemic change is necessary.</p>

                        <p>Finally, the filmmakers establish their ethos by coming across as trustworthy guides through this disturbing material. They use real digital artifacts from the era, home videos, and a serious, documentary approach. No cheap thrills or exploitation. The director and experts interviewed throughout discuss their careful, methodical approach to understanding this tragedy (mentioned around 00:13:30), emphasizing the importance of examining root causes rather than simply condemning the perpetrators. They act like experienced guides, showing you this digital landscape without exaggerating, which lends credibility to their ultimately persuasive message.</p>

                        <p>So what do they want from viewers? The message is clear: as a society, and especially as parents, we need to wake up to how powerful—and sometimes dangerous—the digital world can be for kids. It's not just about limiting screen time anymore. We have to understand the actual content and algorithms shaping young minds. The film pushes for real conversations about digital literacy and mental health. Ignoring online subcultures, they argue, isn't an option if we want to prevent similar tragedies.</p>

                        <p>As a piece meant to persuade, this segment largely succeeds. The filmmakers pull us into the girls' world, not just by telling us what happened, but by making us feel it through every cinematic choice they make. Instead of judging from a distance, we start to understand the complex factors at play. You don't just watch their descent. You're swept along with them, experiencing the disorientation and gradual loss of reality that characterized their journey into obsession.</p>

                        <p>However, there are limitations worth noting. In trying so hard to make us sympathize with the perpetrators, the film almost forgets about the victim and her family. It's a tricky ethical line that pops up frequently in true crime storytelling. We spend so much time understanding Morgan and Anissa that the girl they stabbed becomes almost invisible in the narrative. Additionally, by leaning so heavily on emotional appeals, the film risks flattening out complicated issues like mental illness and placing disproportionate blame on the digital world when factors like Morgan's undiagnosed schizophrenia played crucial roles.</p>

                        <p>Even with those limitations, the segment (and really, the whole film) effectively communicates its message. You leave with this uneasy realization: the real monsters of our online age aren't just the spooky stories or creepy images. It's the systems that let fantasy blur into real life without adequate safeguards or adult supervision. Not seeing this danger for what it is? That's what leads to real harm, and that's precisely what the filmmakers want viewers to understand and act upon.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div id="project3" class="content-section">
                <button class="back-btn" onclick="showHome()">← Back to Home</button>
                <h2>Project 3: Research Podcast - Area 51</h2>
                <div class="project-content" style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
                    
                    <div style="text-align: center; margin: 30px 0; padding: 30px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(0,14,47,0.05), rgba(14,55,114,0.05)); border-radius: 15px;">
                        <div id="podcast-cover" style="width: 300px; height: 300px; margin: 0 auto 20px; background: #000E2F; border-radius: 15px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; color: white; font-size: 1.5em; box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.3);">
                            [Cover Art Placeholder]
                        </div>
                        <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-bottom: 10px;">Area 51: Secrecy, Stories, and the Truth Behind the Legend</h3>
                        <p style="color: #555;"><strong>Hosts:</strong> Bill Onyedire & Shaan</p>
                        <p style="color: #555; margin-top: 10px;"><em>A deep dive into why the Area 51 conspiracy has captured imaginations for decades</em></p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: rgba(14,55,114,0.05); padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 30px 0;">
                        <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-bottom: 15px;">Podcast Overview</h3>
                        <p>This episode explores the enduring legend of Area 51, examining why conspiracy theories about this secretive Nevada military base have persisted for decades. Our central thesis: The legend of Area 51 survives not because of evidence, but because secrecy creates a vacuum that story, emotion, and fear rush in to fill.</p>
                    </div>

                    <h3 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 40px; margin-bottom: 20px; border-bottom: 3px solid #000E2F; padding-bottom: 10px;">Full Podcast Script</h3>

                    <div style="line-height: 1.9; font-size: 1.05em;">
                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (0:05-0:20):</strong> "Okay, Shaan. Be honest with me. If you saw a weird, silent light zig-zagging across the night sky... what's your first thought? Drone? Military tech? Or...?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (0:20-0:35):</strong> "Are you trying to get me to say 'aliens'? My brain says 'drone.' But my heart wants it to be little green men. It's just more fun."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (0:35-1:15):</strong> "That right there—that conflict between what we know and what we want to believe—is the entire story of the place we're talking about today. A dusty, secretive spot in the Nevada desert that has captured the world's imagination for decades: Area 51."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (1:15-2:00):</strong> "Absolutely. So today, we're not just re-hashing the old alien stories. We're asking a bigger question: Why has this legend stuck around so long? Our theory for this episode is a simple one: The legend of Area 51 survives not because of evidence, but because secrecy creates a vacuum. And guess what rushes in to fill that vacuum? Story. Emotion. And a whole lot of fear."</p>

                        <h4 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 35px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.3em;">Key Point 1: Why Area 51 Became a Legend</h4>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (2:00-2:45):</strong> "To understand the modern Area 51 myth, we have to go back to 1989. Enter: Bob Lazar."</p>

                        <p style="font-style: italic; color: #666; margin-left: 20px;">[Short audio clip of Bob Lazar from an old interview: "...it was a gravitational propulsion system... it was like nothing I'd ever seen..."]</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (2:45-3:15):</strong> "Right. This guy shows up on the news, seems totally normal, and claims he was a physicist who reverse-engineered alien spacecraft at a secret site near Area 51 called S-4. He's talking about 'Element 115' and sport models for interstellar travel. It was HUGE. In addition, Lazar specified that Area 51 is divided into many subdivisions, where, for example, they test chemical weapons. Basically, it's broken up into different test areas."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (3:15-3:45):</strong> "It was! But then... the cracks started showing. Outlets like The Guardian dug into his past and found no record of him ever working at Los Alamos or attending MIT or Caltech like he claimed. So, if his story was so flimsy, why did it become the foundation for everything?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (3:45-4:15):</strong> "Conversation Point: Why do you think Lazar's story, specifically, caught fire when others didn't?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (4:15-4:30):</strong> "I think it's because the government gave us nothing. Total radio silence. They didn't even admit the base existed until 2013! When you have a total black hole of information, any story, even a shaky one, feels like a revelation."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (4:30-4:45):</strong> "And in that void, people started seeing UFOs everywhere in Nevada in the 90s. But many of these sightings were almost certainly secret tests of the U-2 and stealth bomber—planes that literally looked like they were from another world."</p>

                        <h4 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 35px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.3em;">Key Point 2: What the Facts Actually Say</h4>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (4:45-5:15):</strong> "Alright, so let's talk about what was actually in that void. When you push the aliens off to the side, the evidence points to something maybe less sci-fi but still incredibly cool. Area 51 is essentially America's top-secret, experimental aviation playground."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (5:15-5:45):</strong> "Exactly. It's been used for developing new aircraft and weapons systems, sometimes decades ahead of their time. The U-2, the Blackbird, the Stealth Fighter—all tested there. These things were so advanced, of course people thought they were UFOs."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (5:45-6:15):</strong> "CONVERSATION POINT: Is the truth more or less interesting than the alien theory?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (6:15-6:30):</strong> "I mean, think about it. You see a silent, black triangle hovering in the sky. That's not an alien—that's multi-billion-dollar human engineering! But because it's behind a fence, we'd rather believe it's from Zeta Reticuli."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (6:30-6:45):</strong> "It's the perfect myth-making environment. As The Guardian put it, it's a 'Cold War relic' built on secrecy. The truth is locked away, so our imaginations run wild."</p>

                        <h4 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 35px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.3em;">Key Point 3: Why the Conspiracy Still Matters</h4>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (6:45-7:15):</strong> "Which brings us to the big question. We know it's probably stealth jets. So why did two million people try to 'Naruto run' their way into the base in 2019? Why does this still have such a grip on us?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (7:15-7:45):</strong> "Because it's not about facts anymore, it's about feelings. Believing in the Area 51 conspiracy is fun. It's exciting. It makes you feel like you're in on a secret that 'THEY' don't want you to know. It's a form of rebellion."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (7:45-8:10):</strong> "And it's wildly popular. A recent YouGov poll found that 43% of Americans think the government is hiding UFO info. That's not a niche group. That's nearly half the country."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (8:10-8:30):</strong> "CONVERSATION POINT: Why do you think this specific conspiracy feels so harmless and fun, when others can be really damaging?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (8:30-8:45):</strong> "But here's the serious part. The Guardian nailed it when they said, 'In the absence of trust, stories fill the cracks.' This isn't just about aliens. It's a symptom of a much bigger erosion of trust in institutions. If people don't trust the government to tell the truth about weather balloons, why would they trust them about... anything else?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (8:45-9:00):</strong> "Right. The stakes aren't about little green men. The stakes are about how this kind of thinking shapes the way we separate fact from fiction, and who we decide to trust."</p>

                        <h4 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 35px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.3em;">Research Discussion</h4>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan:</strong> "Now let's talk about this NPR Fresh Air interview. The guest, Annie Jacobson, a national security reporter for the Los Angeles Times Magazine, discusses her book called 'Area 51'. Her book focuses on the secret surveillance plane projects and nuclear tests done close to Area 51. Jacobson argues that Area 51 has many conspiracies, like UFO sightings and even where the staged moon landing took place due to its secrecy and restrictions from the public."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan:</strong> "During the buildup of the Cold War, the urgency to test more bombs exponentially increased in Area 51. Jacobson said that aircraft such as the U-2 and A-12 Oxcart, aircraft which came out of Area 51, were used as spy planes to conduct espionage on the Soviet Union. She argues that these espionage aircraft kept America safe and out of nuclear warfare. This is an overall grade source; it provides credible and declassified information revealing how the U.S. government historically used Area 51 for atomic bomb testing and the creation of advanced spying technology."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan:</strong> "Let's also take a look at David Jacobs article called 'Unidentified Flying Objects.' This article provides many instances of UFO phenomena in the United States, which first came to public attention in 1947 and continued through the late twentieth and early twenty-first century. It explains how the American government, through the Air Force and its projects, Sign, Grudge, and Blue Book, and also the Federal Bureau of Investigation, the Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies have looked at the UFO phenomenon. In conclusion, almost all research efforts have found that a small but significant number of sightings remain 'unidentified'. According to the article, 'research was difficult although not impossible.' Most of the evidence of UFOs came in pictures and videos, and witness reports. Although no hard evidence has been shown, UFOs have become popular in American culture."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan:</strong> "Let's take a look at our survey to see what others think about Area 51. People are moderately familiar with Area 51, mostly through social media. This shows that people's general knowledge about this topic is from informal or popular sources rather than academic research. Additionally, 60% of people believe the U.S. government is hiding information from the public about activities in Area 51, indicating that skepticism towards the government's transparency regarding Area 51 activities is fairly high."</p>

                        <h4 style="color: #000E2F; margin-top: 35px; margin-bottom: 15px; font-size: 1.3em;">Closing Remarks</h4>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill (9:00-9:30):</strong> "So, where does that leave us? Area 51 might not have aliens, but it's a powerful symbol. It's a blank canvas where we paint our fears, our excitement, and our distrust of authority."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan (9:30-10:00):</strong> "So here's our takeaway. Next time you stumble down a rabbit hole—whether it's about aliens, or something else—just hit pause for one second. And ask yourself: What is this story doing for me? Is it making me feel smart? Excited? Safe in a chaotic world?"</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #000E2F;">Bill:</strong> "Because once you understand the emotion behind the conspiracy, you understand a whole lot more. Thanks for hanging out with us."</p>

                        <p><strong style="color: #0E3772;">Shaan:</strong> "See you in the next one, guys."</p>
                    </div>

                    <div style="background: rgba(0,14,47,0.05); padding: 25px; border-radius: 10px; margin-top: 40px;">
